article.headline: Holy Cross 66, William & Mary 57
article.story: WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) -- Keith Simmons scored 16 points, including five during a decisive 14-2 second half surge, and reserve guard Pat Doherty scored two key field goals during the run in Holy Cross's 66-57 victory over William & Mary Saturday. It was Holy Cross' fifth consecutive win. Adam Payton scored 15 points and Nathan Mann added 12 for William & Mary (1-2). Holy Cross (5-0) had four players in double figures and outrebounding William & Mary 43-32. Holy Cross had a 34-26 halftime advantage, but William & Mary's Corey Cofield scored six points to spark a 16-4 run over 7:55 in the second half, cutting the lead to 34-33. Later in the half, Mann's two field goals brought the Tribe to 42-41, before Payton converted a 3-pointer to tie it at 44-44 with 10:10 left. Simmons, who also had seven steals and two blocked shots, then teamed with Doherty to ignite the Holy Cross rally. Doherty scored back-to-back field goals, the last after a steal, for a 48-44 lead. Simmons then scored a 3-pointer and a basket off an offensive rebound. Moments later, Laimis Kisielius scored on a soaring dunk for the Tribe, but Simmons made a steal, leading to a 3-point play by Torey Thomas. This gave Holy Cross a 58-46 lead with 4:05 remaining. The closest William & Mary came after that was 64-57 with :14 remaining, on a 3-pointer by Mann. William & Mary, which had held Kansas State and Wagner to below 35 percent shooting in its first two games, held Holy Cross to 33 percent during its run. Holy Cross had shot 52 percent in the first half.
